    "summary": "The First Intifada was a Palestinian uprising against Israeli military occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip that began in December 1987 and lasted until 1993. The uprising began spontaneously following a traffic accident in Gaza in which Israeli army trucks killed four Palestinians, but the immediate trigger reflected years of accumulated frustration under two decades of occupation. The intifada was characterized by mass civil disobedience, strikes, stone-throwing by youths against Israeli soldiers, and the emergence of a new generation of Palestinian political leadership.\n\nThe uprising transformed the dynamics of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. The spectacle of Israeli soldiers confronting Palestinian youth throwing stones attracted intense international media attention and generated sympathy for the Palestinian cause globally. The PLO, previously based in Tunis following its expulsion from Lebanon, worked to align itself with the uprising and assert its role as the representative of the Palestinian people.\n\nThe intifada was a significant factor in bringing both sides toward negotiations. Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin recognized that military suppression alone could not resolve the conflict, and the PLO recognized Israel's existence in 1988. These shifts created the conditions for the [[event:2720|Oslo Accords]] of 1993, which formally ended the First Intifada and established a framework for Palestinian self-government.",
